Bivariate Analysis ..¶

This is part of the EDA is mainly about feature distribution by target attribute 'Attrition'

  • Dataset df01 will be used for the purpose of this comparisons as will be illustrated hereunder
  • An Employee who left the Company is termed 'Attrit', plural 'Attrits'
  • Where the term 'Attrit' is utilized, it represents the observations of 'Yes' under 'Attrition' or Employees who have already left company
  • On the other hand, existing company employees will be termed 'Active' and will represent the observations of 'No' under 'Attrition'

# Find correlations with the target and sort
df01_trans = df.copy()

df01_trans['Target'] = df01_trans['Attrition'].apply(
    lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else 1)
df01_trans = df01_trans.drop(
    ['Attrition',], axis=1)

correlations = df01_trans.corr()['Target'].sort_values()
print('Most Positive Correlations: \n', correlations.tail(10))

# Plotting the confusion matrix
def draw_cm(actual, predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

# Running a loop to check different values for 'solver'
# Obtaining the resulting scores for comparison

train_score=[]
test_score=[]
solver = ['newton-cg','lbfgs','liblinear','sag','saga']
for i in solver:
    model = LogisticRegression(random_state=7,penalty='l2', solver=i)  # changing values of solver
    model.fit(xtrain, ytrain) 
    y_predict = model.predict(xtest)     
    train_score.append(round(model.score(xtrain,ytrain),3))
    test_score.append(round(model.score(xtest, ytest),3))
    
print(solver)
print()
print(train_score)
print()
print(test_score)

In [763]:
# Running a loop to check different values for class weight 'C'

train_score=[]                                 
test_score=[]
C = [0.01,0.1,0.25,0.5,0.75,1]
for i in C:
    model = LogisticRegression(random_state=7,penalty='l1',solver='liblinear', C=i)  # changing values of C
    model.fit(xtrain, ytrain) 
    y_predict = model.predict(xtest)     
    train_score.append(round(model.score(xtrain,ytrain),3)) # appending training accuracy in a blank list for every run of the loop
    test_score.append(round(model.score(xtest, ytest),3))   # appending testing accuracy in a blank list for every run of the loop
    
print(C)
print()
print(train_score)
print()
print(test_score)

[0.01, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1]

[0.845, 0.888, 0.899, 0.904, 0.903, 0.904]

[0.823, 0.871, 0.876, 0.875, 0.871, 0.871]

Final Model¶

  • According to the above output, the highest scores of Accuracy for train and test models are obtained using 'solver = liblinear' and 'class weight C = 1'

Confusion Matrix (Final)¶

  • True Positive (TP) (Observed = 1, Prodicted = 1) = 68
  • False Positive (FP) (Ovserved = 0, Prodicted = 1) = 26
  • True Negative (TN) (Observed = 0, Predicted = 0) = 700
  • False Negative (FN) (Observed = 1, Predicted = 0) = 88
Step 06 ..¶

Conclusion and Business Understanding of Model¶

  • Despite that the model performance has improved, there is still room for further improvement in order to obtain better outputs
  • The confusion matrix illustrates the predicted and observed 'attrition' numbers of emoployees
  • Out of the 788 active employees that do not attrite, the model predicts 700 (TN), and 88 (FN).
  • On the other hand, out of the 94 Attrits, 68 (TP) are correctly labelled, and 26 (FP) cases.

As illustrated herein, the stronger correlated factors leading to Attrition includes ..

  • MonthlyIncome
  • DistanceFromHome
  • NumCompaniesWorked
  • PerformanceRating
  • PercentSalaryHike
  • Education
  • YearsSinceLastPromotion
  • RelationshipSatisfaction
  • TrainingTimesLastYear

In addition to other factors that are less correlated to Attrition as illustrated in this analysis.

From a business approach, it is strongly recommended that the company will consider a Retention Plan that will have emphasis on the factors leading to Attrition, while monitoring the active employees that are highly predicted to attrite
